00:19:46.559 --> 00:19:48.577
mechanics is,
in classical theory,

00:19:48.577 --> 00:19:51.819
what's the potential
experienced by the particle?

00:19:51.819 --> 00:19:52.970
That's what you ask.
 

00:19:52.970 --> 00:19:55.717
And it is that potential that
enters this crazy

00:19:55.717 --> 00:19:57.390
Schrödinger equation.
 

00:19:57.390 --> 00:19:59.836
So you need to know classical
mechanics before you can do

00:19:59.836 --> 00:20:00.710
quantum mechanics.
 

00:20:00.710 --> 00:20:03.211
You should know what potential
the particle experiences in

00:20:03.211 --> 00:20:05.450
classical theory,
and stick that into this

00:20:05.450 --> 00:20:08.680
equation to find the allowed
energies in quantum theory.

00:20:08.680 --> 00:20:11.996
So if it's a vibrating system,
there is some omega for

00:20:11.996 --> 00:20:12.808
vibrations.
 

00:20:12.808 --> 00:20:14.646
That ω
is √k/m,

00:20:14.646 --> 00:20:16.930
and you can get k from
that one.

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:19.845
Or if it's a system like an
atom, where there's an electric

00:20:19.845 --> 00:20:22.258
charge between them,
electric force between them,

00:20:22.258 --> 00:20:24.420
you should know the electric
potential.

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:26.426
So you should know the
potential in classical

00:20:26.426 --> 00:20:29.118
mechanics, and then you do the
quantum theory from there.

00:20:29.118 --> 00:20:32.099
So imagine a particle in this
potential in classical theory,

00:20:32.099 --> 00:20:34.473
and you ask yourself,
what does it do in quantum

00:20:34.473 --> 00:20:35.029
theory?
 

00:20:35.029 --> 00:20:39.880
Well, classical theory says,
let's plot the energy of the

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:41.440
particle, right?
 

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:46.013
It's some number that's not
supposed to change as the

00:20:46.013 --> 00:20:47.509
particle moves.
 

00:20:47.509 --> 00:20:51.003
That means here,
if the energy is kinetic

00:20:51.003 --> 00:20:55.808
potential, here the potential is
0, it's all kinetic.

00:20:55.808 --> 00:21:00.150
But as you start going near the
edge, there are two parts here.

00:21:00.150 --> 00:21:04.509
That's the potential and that's
the kinetic.

00:21:04.509 --> 00:21:09.128
And right here,
all the energy is potential,

00:21:09.128 --> 00:21:12.028
and E = potential.
 

00:21:12.028 --> 00:21:15.098
There is no K. What does
that mean?

00:21:15.098 --> 00:21:19.348
That means the particle comes
here, slows down,

00:21:19.348 --> 00:21:22.490
comes to a rest,
then goes back.

00:21:22.490 --> 00:21:26.584
It can never be found here if
it had this energy,

00:21:26.584 --> 00:21:29.568
because it's got more--let's
see.

00:21:29.568 --> 00:21:32.788
It's got more potential energy
than total energy.

00:21:32.788 --> 00:21:34.430
That means it's got negative
kinetic energy.

00:21:34.430 --> 00:21:36.068
That's not possible.
 

00:21:36.068 --> 00:21:39.327
So every classical particle
will execute bounded

00:21:39.327 --> 00:21:43.071
oscillations at any energy,
between what are called the

00:21:43.071 --> 00:21:44.390
turning points.
 

00:21:44.390 --> 00:21:48.673
The left turning point and the
right turning point is as far as

00:21:48.673 --> 00:21:50.608
you can go at that energy.
 

00:21:50.608 --> 00:21:52.778
If you've got more energy,
