00:40:19.019 --> 00:40:19.909
That's not what you want.
 

00:40:19.909 --> 00:40:21.710
You want a nontrivial solution.
 

00:40:21.710 --> 00:40:24.719
So we drop this guy.
 

00:40:24.719 --> 00:40:28.500
But how about n=-1?
 

00:40:28.500 --> 00:40:35.719
Why don't I keep that?
 

00:40:35.719 --> 00:40:37.010
Yes?
 

00:40:37.010 --> 00:40:38.710
Oh, I thought I imagined a hand
going up.

00:40:38.710 --> 00:40:39.500
Yes?
 

00:40:39.500 --> 00:40:42.829
Student: It's the same
thing as -B sine of the

00:40:42.829 --> 00:40:43.789
positive value.
 

00:40:43.789 --> 00:40:45.429
Prof: That's correct.
 

00:40:45.429 --> 00:40:50.389
If you put n=-1,
the function ψ

00:40:50.389 --> 00:40:55.469
of -1 is B
sin(-Πx/L),

00:40:55.469 --> 00:41:01.800
but that = -1 times B
sin(Πx/L).

00:41:01.800 --> 00:41:04.920
This guy is just
ψ_1.

00:41:04.920 --> 00:41:09.902
So it's just a multiple of the
ψ_1 function,

00:41:09.902 --> 00:41:14.010
because -1 times the state is
the same state.

00:41:14.010 --> 00:41:17.188
You don't get a new function;
you just get a multiple of the

00:41:17.188 --> 00:41:18.947
old function,
and in quantum mechanics,

00:41:18.947 --> 00:41:20.059
they're all the same.
 

00:41:20.059 --> 00:41:20.920
But be very careful.
 

00:41:20.920 --> 00:41:25.728
When I did a particle on a
ring, I did e^(ipx/ℏ),

00:41:25.728 --> 00:41:29.947
where I said p =
2Πâ„ /L times any

00:41:29.947 --> 00:41:31.719
integer n.
 

00:41:31.719 --> 00:41:38.929
There I let n = 0, - 1, - 2 etc.
 

00:41:38.929 --> 00:41:41.550
Why did I allow that?
 

00:41:41.550 --> 00:41:43.913
First of all,
in that case,

00:41:43.913 --> 00:41:46.639
e to the i times 0 is not 0.
 

00:41:46.639 --> 00:41:49.429
It's in fact constant.
 

00:41:49.429 --> 00:41:53.014
So for a particle going in a
ring, the 0 momentum state is

00:41:53.014 --> 00:41:54.210
actually allowed.
 

00:41:54.210 --> 00:41:58.677
And 1 and -1 are not the same,
because e^(ipx) and

00:41:58.677 --> 00:42:01.150
e^(-ipx),
forget the ℏ,

00:42:01.150 --> 00:42:04.659
they are not proportional to
each other.

00:42:04.659 --> 00:42:05.960
You understand that?
 

00:42:05.960 --> 00:42:09.650
You can never write
e^(ipx) as a multiple of

00:42:09.650 --> 00:42:10.980
e^(-ipx).
 

00:42:10.980 --> 00:42:12.360
You see that?
 

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:16.615
If there were such a multiple,
let me call the multiple as

00:42:16.615 --> 00:42:20.425
N, then N is
really e^(2ipx) by

00:42:20.425 --> 00:42:22.739
bringing it the other side.
 

00:42:22.739 --> 00:42:25.989
That's certainly not a constant.
 

00:42:25.989 --> 00:42:29.315
So e^(ipx) can never be
converted to e^(-ipx) by

00:42:29.315 --> 00:42:31.931
multiplying by any number,
so it's an independent

00:42:31.931 --> 00:42:32.639
solution.
 

00:42:32.639 --> 00:42:36.440
On the other hand,
sinx and sin(-x)

00:42:36.440 --> 00:42:40.639
are related to each other by a
single factor of -1.

00:42:40.639 --> 00:42:44.751
So that's the reason why in
that case of a particle going in

00:42:44.751 --> 00:42:46.706
a ring,
the solutions are labeled by

00:42:46.706 --> 00:42:48.981
all integers,
positive, negative and 0,

00:42:48.981 --> 00:42:53.300
but a particle in a box,
we label only by positive

00:42:53.300 --> 00:42:54.360
integers.
 

00:42:54.360 --> 00:42:58.045
Negative integers give you the
same function and 0 kills the

00:42:58.045 --> 00:43:00.170
function, so that's not allowed.
 

00:43:00.170 --> 00:43:02.949
Okay, so what about B?
 

00:43:02.949 --> 00:43:05.050
What shall I do with B?
 

00:43:05.050 --> 00:43:11.909
What equation's going to
determine B?

00:43:11.909 --> 00:43:13.360
Yes, any idea?
 

00:43:13.360 --> 00:43:14.030
Yes?
 

00:43:14.030 --> 00:43:15.869
Student: Normalize right?
 

00:43:15.869 --> 00:43:16.369
Prof: Right.
 

00:43:16.369 --> 00:43:18.516
So first of all,
the equation will never tell

00:43:18.516 --> 00:43:19.639
you what B is.
 

00:43:19.639 --> 00:43:21.710
That's what I want you to
understand.

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:25.802
The equation that I've written
here for the energy functions on

00:43:25.802 --> 00:43:27.710
the top,
if size of B is a

00:43:27.710 --> 00:43:30.369
solution, you can multiply both
sides by any number,

00:43:30.369 --> 00:43:32.099
like 15.
 

00:43:32.099 --> 00:43:34.760
Then 15 times ψ
will also be a solution.

00:43:34.760 --> 00:43:38.141
That's a property of a linear
equation that the answer is not

00:43:38.141 --> 00:43:39.550
given in overall scale.
 

00:43:39.550 --> 00:43:41.257
Give me one answer;
I rescale it,

00:43:41.257 --> 00:43:42.659
it's still an answer.
 

00:43:42.659 --> 00:43:45.998
So linear equation will never
tell me the overall size of the

00:43:45.998 --> 00:43:46.610
function.
 

00:43:46.610 --> 00:43:55.010
That is picked by the extra
convenient restriction that

00:43:55.010 --> 00:43:58.900
ψ^(2)dx = 1.
 

00:43:58.900 --> 00:44:04.550
That will determine B
and I'm claiming the answer is

00:44:04.550 --> 00:44:10.199
the √(2/L) is what
you want B to be.

00:44:10.199 --> 00:44:11.320
The answer is again simple.
 

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:14.945
The average value of sine
squared over 1 half period is 1

00:44:14.945 --> 00:44:15.400
half.
 

00:44:15.400 --> 00:44:17.099
If you square or integrate or
whatever,

00:44:17.099 --> 00:44:19.480
you'll get L/2,
so B^(2) times

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:23.300
L/2 should be 1,
and B should therefore

00:44:23.300 --> 00:44:25.599
be the √(2/L).
 

00:44:25.599 --> 00:44:29.083
So let me write down now the
final result of this problem,

00:44:29.083 --> 00:44:31.650
which I think is very,
very instructive.

00:44:31.650 --> 00:44:34.954
If you can follow this much,
you've really got 80 percent of

00:44:34.954 --> 00:44:37.420
the quantum mechanics I want to
teach you.

00:44:37.420 --> 00:44:40.329
If you're comfortable with this
example,

00:44:40.329 --> 00:44:43.429
because we're trying to find
out, in quantum theory,

00:44:43.429 --> 00:44:48.260
you've got a particle in a box,
which is like a hole in the

00:44:48.260 --> 00:44:50.545
floor,
which is so deep that it's

00:44:50.545 --> 00:44:51.550
infinitely deep.
 

00:44:51.550 --> 00:44:53.233
But even if it's not infinite
but very deep,

00:44:53.233 --> 00:44:54.289
the answer's good enough.
 

00:44:54.289 --> 00:44:56.739
You want to know what it will
do.

00:44:56.739 --> 00:45:00.429
In classical mechanics,
what will it do?

00:45:00.429 --> 00:45:04.978
If you're a particle in a box,
what's your lowest energy

00:45:04.978 --> 00:45:05.639
state?
 

00:45:05.639 --> 00:45:06.429
Yes?
 

00:45:06.429 --> 00:45:07.670
Student: Floor of the
box.

00:45:07.670 --> 00:45:10.617
Prof: If you're in
prison with infinitely tall

00:45:10.617 --> 00:45:13.510
walls, you just sit on the floor
and mope, right?

00:45:13.510 --> 00:45:15.639
That's the lowest energy state.
 

00:45:15.639 --> 00:45:17.670
But that's not allowed in
quantum mechanics,

00:45:17.670 --> 00:45:19.510
because you have a definite
x,

00:45:19.510 --> 00:45:21.610
which is wherever you're
sitting, a definite p,

00:45:21.610 --> 00:45:22.650
you're not moving.
 

00:45:22.650 --> 00:45:25.250
Such a state is not allowed.
 

00:45:25.250 --> 00:45:29.322
So in quantum mechanics,
a particle cannot simply sit

00:45:29.322 --> 00:45:29.949
still.
 

00:45:29.949 --> 00:45:34.458
Therefore, it will necessarily
have an uncertainty in position,

00:45:34.458 --> 00:45:37.949
and it will try to spread
itself over the box.

00:45:37.949 --> 00:45:42.210
And the typical uncertainty is
of order.

00:45:42.210 --> 00:45:43.559
If I say, "Where is this
particle?"

00:45:43.559 --> 00:45:44.570
I don't know anything.
 

00:45:44.570 --> 00:45:46.559
It's got to be somewhere in the
box.

00:45:46.559 --> 00:45:48.610
That's the estimate for
Δx.

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:54.250
So Δp has got to
be bigger than â„ /L.

00:45:54.250 --> 00:45:56.019
Forget all the 2Π's.
 

00:45:56.019 --> 00:45:57.400
So it cannot have 0 momentum.
 

00:45:57.400 --> 00:46:00.449
It's momentum has to be
fluctuating with that range.

00:46:00.449 --> 00:46:03.231
And the kinetic energy,
which is in fact the total

00:46:03.231 --> 00:46:08.577
energy inside the box,
which is p^(2)/2m,

00:46:08.577 --> 00:46:15.650
the size of that is
ℏ^(2)/2m L^(2).

00:46:15.650 --> 00:46:18.539
So that is your estimate for
what should be the energy of a

00:46:18.539 --> 00:46:21.429
particle in a box of size
L. So what happens is,

00:46:21.429 --> 00:46:25.170
the box of size L forces
it to have a spread in momentum,

00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:28.186
because you've squeezed it to a
position known to within

00:46:28.186 --> 00:46:28.789
L.
 

00:46:28.789 --> 00:46:31.182
The spread in momentum
translates into spread in

00:46:31.182 --> 00:46:33.344
kinetic energy,
and if I take the spread in

00:46:33.344 --> 00:46:36.021
kinetic energy to be a rough
estimate of the lowest kinetic

00:46:36.021 --> 00:46:39.085
energy I could have,
you get a number which except

00:46:39.085 --> 00:46:42.389
for factors of Π
is in fact the right answer.

00:46:42.389 --> 00:46:46.076
So people always estimate
energies of particles by doing

00:46:46.076 --> 00:46:47.349
this calculation.
 

00:46:47.349 --> 00:46:49.092
For example,
take a nucleus,

00:46:49.092 --> 00:46:51.610
which is 10^(-13) centimeters
across.

00:46:51.610 --> 00:46:52.920
I put a proton there.
 

00:46:52.920 --> 00:46:55.849
What's the minimum kinetic
energy of that proton?

00:46:55.849 --> 00:46:58.838
You find by the following
method: Δx is

00:46:58.838 --> 00:47:01.768
10^(-13), because it's somewhere
in the nucleus.

00:47:01.768 --> 00:47:03.858
Δp is that,
and you do that,

00:47:03.858 --> 00:47:05.268
you will get some energy.
 

00:47:05.268 --> 00:47:09.398
That will be the typical energy
of a particle inside the

00:47:09.398 --> 00:47:10.150
nucleus.
 

00:47:10.150 --> 00:47:13.130
So particles inside the nucleus
cannot sit still.

00:47:13.130 --> 00:47:15.320
More you cram them,
it's like children.

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:18.349
You put them in a tighter room,
they're jiggling more and more.

00:47:18.349 --> 00:47:20.760
That's called zero point motion.
 

00:47:20.760 --> 00:47:23.302
You cannot just nail them in
x without letting them

00:47:23.302 --> 00:47:24.239
spread in p.
 

00:47:24.239 --> 00:47:27.867
That means you cannot get the
lowest energy So lowest energy

00:47:27.867 --> 00:47:31.739
is some number you can estimate
by the uncertainty principle.

00:47:31.739 --> 00:47:36.251
So the next question was,
let's take one of these

00:47:36.251 --> 00:47:40.577
functions, say ψ's of 3,
the square root of

00:47:40.577 --> 00:47:44.150
(2/L)sin(
3Πx/L).

