way.
 

00:52:44.750 --> 00:52:47.420
Then I have to find
A_n.

00:52:47.420 --> 00:52:51.148
And if I want to find
A_n,

00:52:51.148 --> 00:52:56.119
that = integral of (2/L)
sin(nΠx/L).

00:52:56.119 --> 00:52:57.927
If you want,
you can put a conjugate,

00:52:57.927 --> 00:53:00.239
but it doesn't matter,
because sine is real.

00:53:00.239 --> 00:53:03.960
Multiply it by Mr. Crazy
here, whatever it is,

00:53:03.960 --> 00:53:06.110
and do their integral.
 

00:53:06.110 --> 00:53:09.500
It will give you some number
for every n.

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:10.867
A_1,
A_2,

00:53:10.867 --> 00:53:12.280
A_3,
A_4,

00:53:12.280 --> 00:53:15.018
and the square of every one of
them will give you the odds that

00:53:15.018 --> 00:53:17.356
you will find this energy or
that energy or some other

00:53:17.356 --> 00:53:18.018
energy.
 

00:53:18.018 --> 00:53:21.498
So what quantum mechanics tells
you is, an energy measurement of

00:53:21.498 --> 00:53:24.260
a particle in a box cannot give
a random answer.

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:26.389
It can only give one of these
answers.

00:53:26.389 --> 00:53:28.940
That's the quantization of
energy.

00:53:28.940 --> 00:53:32.911
It does not mean every particle
in a box is in a state of

00:53:32.911 --> 00:53:34.190
definite energy.
 

00:53:34.190 --> 00:53:37.014
A particle in a box can be any
wave function,

00:53:37.014 --> 00:53:40.608
provided it vanishes at the
ends and doesn't spill out of

00:53:40.608 --> 00:53:42.469
the infinitely tall wall.
 

00:53:42.469 --> 00:53:44.405
So for every one of them,
you can ask the usual

00:53:44.405 --> 00:53:46.510
questions: what happens when I
measure position?

00:53:46.510 --> 00:53:47.750
Square the function.
 

00:53:47.750 --> 00:53:49.268
What happens when I measure
momentum?

00:53:49.268 --> 00:53:51.800
Write it in terms of e
to the ipx functions.

00:53:51.800 --> 00:53:53.309
What happens when I measure
energy?

00:53:53.309 --> 00:53:56.809
Write it in terms of these
functions.

00:53:56.809 --> 00:54:03.579
Okay?
 

00:54:03.579 --> 00:54:07.121
All right, so I want to do one
last topic here,

00:54:07.121 --> 00:54:11.280
which is called scattering,
but I don't want to proceed

00:54:11.280 --> 00:54:14.670
till you guys have understood
this part.

00:54:14.670 --> 00:54:17.409
This is covered in all the
books and maybe you can read the

00:54:17.409 --> 00:54:18.969
books or you can read my notes.
 

00:54:18.969 --> 00:54:21.039
You can talk to everybody.
 

00:54:21.039 --> 00:54:24.525
But we have solved--from this,
all quantum problems that we

00:54:24.525 --> 00:54:27.409
all do are exactly isomorphic to
this problem.

00:54:27.409 --> 00:54:30.007
It's the same thing we do over
and over again,

00:54:30.007 --> 00:54:33.010
except the equations you solve
are more difficult.

00:54:33.010 --> 00:54:33.929
They can be in higher
dimensions.

00:54:33.929 --> 00:54:37.260
They can involve more than one
particle.

00:54:37.260 --> 00:54:40.110
The potential could be
complicated, but the philosophy

00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:41.239
is always the same.
 

00:54:41.239 --> 00:54:43.039
There'll be some
Schrödinger equation,

00:54:43.039 --> 00:54:45.969
and you want to find all the
functions that satisfy it,

00:54:45.969 --> 00:54:49.760
find the allowed energies and
the allowed functions.

00:54:49.760 --> 00:54:52.070
We will see that states of
definite energy have a very

00:54:52.070 --> 00:54:53.768
privileged role in quantum
mechanics.

00:54:53.768 --> 00:54:57.639
That will be clear in the next
two lectures.

00:54:57.639 --> 00:55:01.940
But right now,
here's what I want to do.

00:55:01.940 --> 00:55:05.099
This is a very small variation
of what we have done,

00:55:05.099 --> 00:55:07.639
so most of the hard work has
been done.

00:55:07.639 --> 00:55:10.320
I'm just going to cash in on
that.

00:55:10.320 --> 00:55:15.574
Take the following problem in
classical mechanics:

00:55:15.574 --> 00:55:18.469
here is the level ground.
 

00:55:18.469 --> 00:55:23.980
Then I make a little change in
the landscape so that this has

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:28.940
got certain height and therefore
certain potential,

00:55:28.940 --> 00:55:31.809
V_0. And from
this end,

00:55:31.809 --> 00:55:35.619
I roll a marble and see what
happens.

00:55:35.619 --> 00:55:40.733
The marble is given some energy
E, which because there is

00:55:40.733 --> 00:55:44.550
no potential here,
it's just p^(2)/2m.

00:55:44.550 --> 00:55:48.599
Question is, what will happen?
 

00:55:48.599 --> 00:55:52.313
Can you tell me what will
happen in this problem,

00:55:52.313 --> 00:55:53.630
to this marble?
 

00:55:53.630 --> 00:55:55.885
Student: Don't we have
to use the Schrödinger

00:55:55.885 --> 00:55:56.369
equations?
 

00:55:56.369 --> 00:55:57.039
Prof: No.
 

00:55:57.039 --> 00:55:57.920
Classical mechanics.
 

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:00.326
Student: Oh,
the marble will only go up as

00:56:00.326 --> 00:56:03.284
far as it has the amount of
energy that that would equal the

00:56:03.284 --> 00:56:05.039
potential energy at that point.
 

00:56:05.039 --> 00:56:05.550
Prof: That's correct.
 

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:09.170
So he said it will go as far as
energy equals potential,

00:56:09.170 --> 00:56:11.869
so let p^(2)/2m have
this value.

00:56:11.869 --> 00:56:12.809
That's my energy.
 

00:56:12.809 --> 00:56:13.889
And it does not change.
 

00:56:13.889 --> 00:56:15.960
That's the law of conservation
of energy.

00:56:15.960 --> 00:56:20.083
So here, since energy is
kinetic potential,

00:56:20.083 --> 00:56:21.949
it's all kinetic.
 

00:56:21.949 --> 00:56:26.880
Somewhere here,
that part of it is potential;

00:56:26.880 --> 00:56:28.739
the rest of it is kinetic.
 

00:56:28.739 --> 00:56:31.280
Here kinetic vanishes.
 

00:56:31.280 --> 00:56:34.018
Here you're not allowed.
 

00:56:34.018 --> 00:56:37.311
So you will go,
you will climb that far and

00:56:37.311 --> 00:56:38.800
you'll come back.
 

00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:45.023
But if your initial energy was
that, then you will come here,

00:56:45.023 --> 00:56:46.889
going very fast.
 

00:56:46.889 --> 00:56:50.798
You will slow down,
but you still make it on the

00:56:50.798 --> 00:56:53.960
other side, but with lower
velocity.

00:56:53.960 --> 00:56:55.010
That's very simple.
 

00:56:55.010 --> 00:56:56.320
There's only one answer you can
get.

00:56:56.320 --> 00:56:57.469
You throw something.
 

00:56:57.469 --> 00:56:59.902
If it comes back,
it means the barrier is taller

00:56:59.902 --> 00:57:00.989
than what you have.
 

00:57:00.989 --> 00:57:03.579
Suppose you cannot see this
barrier.

00:57:03.579 --> 00:57:05.914
All you have is a marble,
and you want to know how tall

00:57:05.914 --> 00:57:06.650
the barrier is.
 

00:57:06.650 --> 00:57:07.480
Very easy.
 

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:09.130
Throw the marble at a known
speed.

00:57:09.130 --> 00:57:12.367
If it comes back,
then you haven't reached the

00:57:12.367 --> 00:57:13.880
top of the barrier.
 

00:57:13.880 --> 00:57:17.079
Keep on increasing the kinetic
energy till one day it doesn't

00:57:17.079 --> 00:57:17.719
come back.
 

00:57:17.719 --> 00:57:19.699
That's when you're sitting
right here.

00:57:19.699 --> 00:57:23.072
That's one way to tell how tall
this hill is without actually

00:57:23.072 --> 00:57:23.860
going there.
 

00:57:23.860 --> 00:57:27.684
But now what I want to do is do
a quantum mechanical experiment

00:57:27.684 --> 00:57:29.659
in exactly the same situation.
 

00:57:29.659 --> 00:57:38.362
I want to send a particle from
the left and I want to see what

00:57:38.362 --> 00:57:39.789
happens.
 

00:57:39.789 --> 00:57:43.293
So now, to simplify the
problem, I'm going to take the

00:57:43.293 --> 00:57:45.940
potential to again have only 2
values.

00:57:45.940 --> 00:57:49.922
At x = 0,
it jumps to a value

00:57:49.922 --> 00:57:52.539
V_0.
 

00:57:52.539 --> 00:57:55.838
So this problem is just the
Schrödinger equation in the

00:57:55.838 --> 00:57:59.250
left region, Schrödinger
equation in the right region.

00:57:59.250 --> 00:58:03.255
So I'm going to spare you some
of the calculations,

00:58:03.255 --> 00:58:05.420
because it's so familiar.
 

00:58:05.420 --> 00:58:13.240
One will look like Ae^(ikx)
Be^(-ikx),

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:21.239
where k^(2) is just
2mE/ℏ^(2),

00:58:21.239 --> 00:58:22.840
here.
 

00:58:22.840 --> 00:58:27.344
First, let's take a case where
E is bigger than

00:58:27.344 --> 00:58:29.809
V_0,
okay?

00:58:29.809 --> 00:58:32.449
Then I go to region II.
 

00:58:32.449 --> 00:58:35.148
Region II I've got to solve the
Schrödinger equation with a

00:58:35.148 --> 00:58:36.389
V_0 in it.
 

00:58:36.389 --> 00:58:41.715
Then you will find in region
II, ψ II looks like

00:58:41.715 --> 00:58:46.309
Ce^(ik'x)
De^(−ik'x),

00:58:46.309 --> 00:58:52.201
where k'^(2) will be
2m times E -

00:58:52.201 --> 00:58:57.010
V_0 over
ℏ^(2).

00:58:57.010 --> 00:58:59.219
Because when you have a
potential, you must always

00:58:59.219 --> 00:59:00.617
have--
look at the Schrödinger

00:59:00.617 --> 00:59:04.378
equation here--
2m/ℏ^(2) at E -

00:59:04.378 --> 00:59:05.199
V.
 

00:59:05.199 --> 00:59:06.550
So E is not 0.
 

00:59:06.550 --> 00:59:09.559
The k' now,
so what does this mean?

00:59:09.559 --> 00:59:13.579
You can see very simply,
it's got some momentum here.

00:59:13.579 --> 00:59:16.496
It's got a smaller momentum
here, because k'^(2) is

00:59:16.496 --> 00:59:18.800
going to be smaller than
k^(2), because

00:59:18.800 --> 00:59:20.949
V_0 is non-zero
here.

00:59:20.949 --> 00:59:24.813
That is just the statement that
when the particle's moving here,

00:59:24.813 --> 00:59:28.371
it's slower than when it's
here, because it has to climb up

00:59:28.371 --> 00:59:29.170
the hill.
 

00:59:29.170 --> 00:59:34.137
So the wave functions in this
region has got an incoming,

00:59:34.137 --> 00:59:38.130
right moving wave of momentum,
ℏk.

00:59:38.130 --> 00:59:41.730
It's got to reflect that wave
of momentum -ℏk.

00:59:41.730 --> 00:59:45.795
And in this region again,
it's got a right moving and a

00:59:45.795 --> 00:59:50.239
left moving, because this
k can be of either sign.

00:59:50.239 --> 00:59:51.384
So you can pick the
coefficients,

00:59:51.384 --> 00:59:53.242
A,
B, C, D arbitrarily,

00:59:53.242 --> 00:59:55.800
but I'm going to choose
D = 0,

00:59:55.800 --> 00:59:59.929
because what I have in mind is
a problem where the particle

00:59:59.929 --> 01:00:02.280
actually came in from the left.
 

01:00:02.280 --> 01:00:05.579
If it came in from the left,
I'm prepared for some of it

01:00:05.579 --> 01:00:08.219
coming back reflected,
and some of it getting

01:00:08.219 --> 01:00:09.179
transmitted.
 

01:00:09.179 --> 01:00:11.371
There's nobody coming in from
the right at infinity,

01:00:11.371 --> 01:00:13.349
because I'm not sending
anything from there.

01:00:13.349 --> 01:00:15.170
I'm sending my particle from
the left.

01:00:15.170 --> 01:00:19.202
So I pick a solution in which
D, which is anything,

01:00:19.202 --> 01:00:20.760
I pick that to be 0.
 

01:00:20.760 --> 01:00:24.889
So here are my two solutions.
 

01:00:24.889 --> 01:00:28.771
I hope you understand that
k and k' are not

01:00:28.771 --> 01:00:30.018
the same number.
 

01:00:30.018 --> 01:00:32.425
k' is smaller because
the momentum on the right hand

01:00:32.425 --> 01:00:34.664
side is going to be less,
because some of it's eaten up

01:00:34.664 --> 01:00:35.659
by potential energy.
 

01:00:35.659 --> 01:00:38.469
So what people do is they draw
a picture like this.

01:00:38.469 --> 01:00:41.606
They draw a wave that's going
at some speed,

01:00:41.606 --> 01:00:45.110
and it comes in this region and
it slows down.

01:00:45.110 --> 01:00:47.219
That's what the function will
look like.

01:00:47.219 --> 01:00:48.829
The real function's made of
exponentials,

01:00:48.829 --> 01:00:51.141
but the real and imaginary
parts will have rapid

01:00:51.141 --> 01:00:54.239
oscillations on the left and
slow oscillations on the right,

01:00:54.239 --> 01:00:58.110
because k is bigger than
k'.

01:00:58.110 --> 01:00:58.539
Very good.
 

01:00:58.539 --> 01:01:02.804
So now I have the following
condition: at the interface

01:01:02.804 --> 01:01:07.228
where the two regions meet,
the ψ must match from the

01:01:07.228 --> 01:01:09.440
left and from the right.
 

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:12.335
So x = 0,
coming from the left,

01:01:12.335 --> 01:01:16.246
I want ψ_1 at 0
should be the same at

01:01:16.246 --> 01:01:18.360
ψ_2 at 0.
 

01:01:18.360 --> 01:01:24.650
That will tell me that A B =
C.

01:01:24.650 --> 01:01:30.166
Because if you put x =
0, all the exponentials become

01:01:30.166 --> 01:01:33.719
one, and A B must =
C.

01:01:33.719 --> 01:01:36.695
There's the condition that if
you come from the two sides,

01:01:36.695 --> 01:01:38.420
the wave function has to match.
 

01:01:38.420 --> 01:01:41.894
But in the Schrödinger
theory, you make a second

01:01:41.894 --> 01:01:44.969
requirement that the derivatives
also match.

01:01:44.969 --> 01:01:49.690
The two functions coming from
the left and right cannot join

01:01:49.690 --> 01:01:50.650
like this.
 

01:01:50.650 --> 01:01:53.889
They must join with the same
slope.

01:01:53.889 --> 01:01:57.460
The reason the slope must be
the same is that if the slope

01:01:57.460 --> 01:02:01.159
changed abruptly at one point,
the rate of change of slope

01:02:01.159 --> 01:02:03.942
will be infinite there,
because d^(2)ψ/dx^(2)

01:02:03.942 --> 01:02:05.760
is the rate of change of the
slope.

01:02:05.760 --> 01:02:07.320
But in the Schrödinger
equation,

01:02:07.320 --> 01:02:09.909
the second derivative ψ,
if it's infinite,

01:02:09.909 --> 01:02:12.360
there is no compensating terms
in the equation,

01:02:12.360 --> 01:02:14.630
because E and V
are all finite.

01:02:14.630 --> 01:02:17.257
So that infinity will not be
balanced, so you can never have

01:02:17.257 --> 01:02:17.570
that.
 

01:02:17.570 --> 01:02:19.010
So second derivative must be
finite;

01:02:19.010 --> 01:02:21.000
first derivative must be
continuous.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:26.987
So I make the requirement that
dψ/dx in region I at

01:02:26.987 --> 01:02:32.090
x = 0 must match
dψ II dx at

01:02:32.090 --> 01:02:33.760
x = 0.
 

01:02:33.760 --> 01:02:35.679
What does that give me?
 

01:02:35.679 --> 01:02:42.929
Well, take the derivative and
equate them at x = 0,

01:02:42.929 --> 01:02:51.070
you'll find ik times A - B
= ik' times C.

01:02:51.070 --> 01:02:55.442
Take the derivative and then
equate the derivatives at

01:02:55.442 --> 01:02:56.679
x = 0.
 

01:02:56.679 --> 01:02:58.445
Derivatives brings down
ik for this,

01:02:58.445 --> 01:02:59.369
-ik for that.
 

01:02:59.369 --> 01:03:02.570
Blah, blah, you put them
together.

01:03:02.570 --> 01:03:05.980
So these are the two conditions.
 

01:03:05.980 --> 01:03:10.487
Now what causes mild panic is
that I have three unknowns and

01:03:10.487 --> 01:03:11.710
two equations.
 

01:03:11.710 --> 01:03:13.807
I've got A,
B and C,

01:03:13.807 --> 01:03:15.969
and I've got only two
equations.

01:03:15.969 --> 01:03:22.079
So what do you think is going
on?

01:03:22.079 --> 01:03:29.320
Anybody have an idea?
 

01:03:29.320 --> 01:03:31.659
It's that even in the particle
in a box,

01:03:31.659 --> 01:03:34.483
you'll remember the overall
height of the wave function is

01:03:34.483 --> 01:03:37.059
never determined by the
Schrödinger equation.

01:03:37.059 --> 01:03:38.219
It's whatever you like.
 

01:03:38.219 --> 01:03:43.119
So what people do is they say,
"Let's pick A =

01:03:43.119 --> 01:03:43.980
1."
 

01:03:43.980 --> 01:03:46.369
That sets the overall height
arbitrarily.

01:03:46.369 --> 01:03:54.793
Then I get 1 B = C and
ik times 1 - B =

01:03:54.793 --> 01:03:56.650
ik' [C}.
 

01:03:56.650 --> 01:03:59.931
Now of course you can solve
for B and you can solve

01:03:59.931 --> 01:04:00.739
for C.
 

01:04:00.739 --> 01:04:03.518
I'm not going to do that here;
it's very easy.

01:04:03.518 --> 01:04:11.730
You're going to find B = k
− k' over k k'.

01:04:11.730 --> 01:04:19.349
You're going to find C =
2k over k k'.

01:04:19.349 --> 01:04:22.579
That's simple algebra of
simultaneous equations.

01:04:22.579 --> 01:04:27.119
I want you to look at the
answer.

01:04:27.119 --> 01:04:30.809
You remember now what A,
B and C are.

01:04:30.809 --> 01:04:34.900
A comes in,
B goes back and C

01:04:34.900 --> 01:04:36.570
goes to the right.
 

01:04:36.570 --> 01:04:41.940
What do you find strange about
the answer?

01:04:41.940 --> 01:04:47.458
It's that if you came in from
the left with an energy bigger

01:04:47.458 --> 01:04:51.760
than the barrier,
there's a certain probability

01:04:51.760 --> 01:04:54.659
that you will go backwards.
 

01:04:54.659 --> 01:04:56.525
In classical mechanics,
if your energy is more than the

01:04:56.525 --> 01:04:57.769
barrier, you will never come
back.

01:04:57.769 --> 01:04:58.639
The probability is 0.
 

01:04:58.639 --> 01:05:00.947
In quantum theory,
even though your energy is more

01:05:00.947 --> 01:05:03.876
than the barrier,
there's a certain probability

01:05:03.876 --> 01:05:08.329
you'll get reflected and certain
probability to get transmitted.

01:05:08.329 --> 01:05:10.880
The square of this is like the
odds of going to the right.

01:05:10.880 --> 01:05:13.530
The square of this is like the
odds of getting reflected.

01:05:13.530 --> 01:05:17.411
The point is the reflection
probability does not vanish even

01:05:17.411 --> 01:05:20.699
if the energy is bigger than the
barrier height.

01:05:20.699 --> 01:05:23.710
That's because this is quantum
mechanics and you're really

01:05:23.710 --> 01:05:25.768
dealing with waves and not
particles.

01:05:25.768 --> 01:05:28.940
And waves have the property
that when the medium changes,

01:05:28.940 --> 01:05:30.469
there is some reflection.
 

01:05:30.469 --> 01:05:33.849
And to the quantum mechanical
wave ψ,

01:05:33.849 --> 01:05:36.539
a barrier looks like a change
in refractive index,

01:05:36.539 --> 01:05:39.809
so it will get reflected and
some will get transmitted.

01:05:39.809 --> 01:05:42.474
But the interesting thing is,
in the quantum problem,

01:05:42.474 --> 01:05:45.550
you can send your billiard ball
to find how tall the mountain

01:05:45.550 --> 01:05:45.909
is.
 

01:05:45.909 --> 01:05:48.231
And even if the energy was more
than the mountain,

01:05:48.231 --> 01:05:49.559
sometimes it'll come back.
 

01:05:49.559 --> 01:05:53.449
So that's not a reliable way to
measure that.

01:05:53.449 --> 01:05:57.154
The last example is,
what if your energy is less

01:05:57.154 --> 01:05:58.099
than this?
 

01:05:58.099 --> 01:06:03.480
What if your energy is like
here, lower than the barrier?

01:06:03.480 --> 01:06:07.956
If you're lower than the
barrier, you will find that

01:06:07.956 --> 01:06:12.518
k' will equal i
times some κ,

01:06:12.518 --> 01:06:17.576
because it will become
imaginary, and you will have

01:06:17.576 --> 01:06:21.518
then a function that looks like
this.

01:06:21.518 --> 01:06:24.938
The function will oscillate,
then it will die exponentially

01:06:24.938 --> 01:06:25.940
in this region.
 

01:06:25.940 --> 01:06:29.409
It's exactly what I did
earlier, like particle in a box.

01:06:29.409 --> 01:06:34.556
In the classically forbidden
region, it goes a little

01:06:34.556 --> 01:06:37.329
distance but not very far.
 

01:06:37.329 --> 01:06:40.190
So it does get reflected if the
energy is less,

01:06:40.190 --> 01:06:44.108
but you can actually find it in
a region where it's not supposed

01:06:44.108 --> 01:06:44.730
to be.
 

01:06:44.730 --> 01:06:47.951
And you can say that's going to
be very embarrassing for the

01:06:47.951 --> 01:06:50.791
particle to be found here,
because its kinetic energy

01:06:50.791 --> 01:06:52.320
should be negative here.
 

01:06:52.320 --> 01:06:55.179
So what's the particle say to
you when you catch it there?

01:06:55.179 --> 01:06:57.510
It will say,
"In order to locate me

01:06:57.510 --> 01:06:59.434
here,
you shine some light on me,

01:06:59.434 --> 01:07:02.485
and the energy I got from the
photon made me legitimate in

01:07:02.485 --> 01:07:03.610
that region."
 

01:07:03.610 --> 01:07:05.510
It will come back to positive
energy.

01:07:05.510 --> 01:07:08.487
So the act of measurement will
prevent it from ever being

01:07:08.487 --> 01:07:11.041
caught in that region,
but it's got an amplitude,

01:07:11.041 --> 01:07:13.010
a probability to be caught
there.

01:07:13.010 --> 01:07:16.010
Final thing I want to mention
is, if this barrier,

01:07:16.010 --> 01:07:20.829
instead of going on forever,
terminated there and became 0

01:07:20.829 --> 01:07:23.570
again,
this will leak out here and

01:07:23.570 --> 01:07:27.530
start going out with the same
wavelength as that one.

01:07:27.530 --> 01:07:30.010
That's called barrier
penetration.

01:07:30.010 --> 01:07:32.635
That means if you send a
particle here with an energy not

01:07:32.635 --> 01:07:35.309
enough to overcome the barrier
in classical mechanics,

01:07:35.309 --> 01:07:38.057
in quantum mechanics,
it's got a small chance of

01:07:38.057 --> 01:07:39.929
being found on the other side.
 

01:07:39.929 --> 01:07:42.070
On the other side,
it can go scot free.

01:07:42.070 --> 01:07:44.983
It's not allowed in this
region, because there the

01:07:44.983 --> 01:07:46.710
kinetic energy is negative.
 

01:07:46.710 --> 01:07:51.391
Here kinetic energy is the same
as before, except the height may

01:07:51.391 --> 01:07:52.579
be very small.
 

01:07:52.579 --> 01:07:56.512
So this means no barrier is
completely safe in quantum

01:07:56.512 --> 01:07:57.179
theory.
 

01:07:57.179 --> 01:08:00.659
